    <h2>Build trust and give users a positive experience of care</h2>

     <p>Do not rush things. Ask for information at the appropriate time. <a href="/service-manual/content/how-to-write-good-questions-for-forms/3-consider-the-sensitivities-around-your-questions">Consider the sensitivities around your questions</a>. Be respectful and inclusive.</p>
    <p>Balance moving users through the task with prompts, reassurance and explanations. (But do not try to reassure people by describing the task as "easy" or "simple".) Offer help: on the web, on phone or in person. Use <a href="/service-manual/content/how-to-write-good-questions-for-forms/7-write-the-supporting-content-for-your-form#help-text">help text</a>, <a href="/service-manual/content/how-to-write-good-questions-for-forms/7-write-the-supporting-content-for-your-form#error-messages">error messages</a> and guidance in the form. Help people understand their mistakes and make it easy for them to get support.</p>

    <h2>Think about where your user will be when they fill in the form</h2>
    <p>Will they be at home, on their mobile, or using someone else's phone in an emergency, for example? How they will be feeling?</p>
    <p>Will they be filling in the form themselves? If someone may be filling in the form for them, that may change how appropriate the question is.</p>
  <details class="nhsuk-details">
