     <h2>Use clear language that users understand</h2>

    <p>Use familiar words in familiar ways. Listen to your users to get an idea of the language they use: for example, (high) "blood pressure", not "hypertension". Find out how they describe the information you're asking them for.</p>
    <p>Do not hide behind the passive tense. Not "Your GP will be notified' but "We will let your GP know".</p>

    <h2>Be less formal</h2>
    <p>Ask questions the way you would in person. Soften your language. Instead of "You must confirm this", explain "Before you continue, you need to confirm this". Try reading your questions to a colleague and listening to how they answer them.</p>
    <p>Do not just repeat a message if someone gets things wrong a second time. It can feel harsh. Think about how you could rephrase it.</p>
    <p>Do not ask for the users' "Full name", for example, if you just need their "Name" or "Contact name". (But be clear whose name you're asking for. For example, do not rely on a page title "Next of kin" and then ask for their "Name". Say "Name of next of kin".)</p>

    <h3>But avoid using "Please"</h3>
    <p>"Please" suggests that people have a choice. Sometimes it can feel patronising. It's not usually necessary.</p>

    <h2>Use "I" and "you" appropriately</h2>
    <p>Use "you" or "your" when you're asking questions, giving instructions or describing things. For example: "Have you changed your name?"</p>
    <p>Use "I" or "me" for things that the user will do or say, for example when they click a button or select a checkbox. For example: "Add me". But only use "I" or "me" when you need to.</p>
    <p>Check how this works by talking through your questions with a colleague, one of you playing the computer, the other answering as the user.</p>


    <h2>Make the conversation flow</h2>
    <p>Word questions or statements consistently. This helps users get into a rhythm of answering and lets them focus on the content of the questions rather than how they’re presented.</p>
    <p>It's OK to ask a follow up question. For example: "We think you mean this. Is that right?". You do not need to validate the question on the same page. Sometimes it's more effective to check it on the next page.</p>
